tip.text:
As soon as you enter the room here you’ll know you've found the right conditions to soothe the nut. In a beautiful circular church, lit by candles and pink and purple hues, this is a sound gong bath. What would your school friends say if they could see you now? They'd be very impressed, we'd wager. You’ll lie on a mat with your head towards the gongs, covered by rugs and feeling all snug, ready to let the mind drift to wherever it fancies.

The gongs and Tibetan singing bowls create deep and immersive waves of sound that are richly atmospheric - sometimes sparse, sometimes layered, and occasionally apocalyptic but not in a scary way. It's a pretty unique experience: you might be transported off to some distant galaxy, you might keep thinking about what you’re going to eat afterwards. But one thing is for sure - it is relaxing.

The Psychedelic Society put on plenty of similar events to this - from dancing in the dark to song circles, inner visions and a host of talks. The use of psychedelics is not encouraged, though were you to come to this on acid or something you would probably have a blast. Check their website for upcoming events.

Located in a disused Victorian tram depot in Clapton, BLOK is a functional gym space/gallery/lighting installation/cafe - and it's pretty darn innovative to say the least. With over 20-odd classes, you can get involved with anything from boxing, to strength and conditioning classes, HIIT, yoga, barre and Pilates. The on-site cafe offers up the likes of bone broth, Square Mile coffee and juices.

Surrounded by exposed brick walls, high concrete ceilings and tramlines, you can only expect to pay a lot of mulla here for each class, at around £14 a pop.

If you're sick of downward dogging in your boring generic yoga class, kick it up a notch (or ten) at one of the Refinery's buzzy fitness sessions. They're all about the fun at this sleek Hackney studio, injecting some serious spunk into a wide array of yoga, barre, and cardio classes. You want a ballet and boxing fusion class? Fancy a funky Friday flow? A sexy Saturday core class? A disco-themed barre bustle? They've got it all, for a £14-15 drop-in fee.

For those of you who think getting out of exercise by calling it "boring" is a good enough excuse... with disco barre on the scene, you haven't got a leg to stand on anymore. This ballet barre-based work out will totally transform your body and put the groove back into your funk.

Become a slave to the rhythm rather than the treadmill, as you point and stretch under the glimmer of the disco ball.

Drop in classes: £12 on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays.

Hotpod Yoga's signature class is like doing hot yoga in the womb. It all goes down in their futuristic, cocoon-like pods, heated to 37 degrees and designed to make yogis feel like they're in another world. The vibes inside are chill as hell - purple lighting, good tunes, and aromatherapy scents all make Hotpod a rejuvenating practice. Choose between their beginner or intermediate flow classes, both rooted in vinyasa tailored to counteract the stresses of everyday life.

Single class pass - £14; off-peak class pass - £12. They also have locations in Brixton and Notting Hill.

After what feels like a horrible eternity, London Fields lido is back up and running. This is the rarest of gems in London: a heated 50m outdoor pool with decent facilities to boot where inconceivably spritely speedo-clad swimmers glide up and down the lanes without losing their breath. They have swimming lessons for children and adults, a sunbathing area, cafe and swimfit sessions too. It gets super busy here in the summer and is probably best avoided on hot days.

Release your inner Beyonce at this hula fitness class. Swing your hips to carve out those washboard abs and thin out those thighs. This class also aids coordination and zaps calories. Plus, we shouldn't have to mention that playing with a hula hoop for an hour is loads of fun. There are also classes in Kennington, Westbourne Grove, Kings Cross, and Paddington.

Ticket Price - £8

There are plenty of fit and flexible sorts knocking around London Fields and this place might be the reason why. Run by Sapan, this gym and fitness studio hidden away beneath the arches on Mentmore Terrace put on plenty of classes including spin cycling, weekend boot camps, vinyasa yoga, pilates and a menacing-sounding warriors circuit.

No joining fee or costly memberships - drop in and take part in a class which are normally between £5-10. There's also a £20 monthly pass which'll let you go to as many as you like - though booking might be required.

Have you ever looked at your gym's weekly class schedule and felt overwhelmed by all the things on offer? Yoga, pilates, dance, plyometrics... who's got the time? Maybe an Instagram fitness guru, but you're just a humble 9-6 worker with limited time to sculpt a crackin' bod.

Enter Popfit's new fitness hybrid - they're rolling all the aforementioned fitness styles into super sweaty, high energy classes that offer full-body conditioning and fun times. Pick your poison: their Signature class, combining yoga, pilates, dance, and plyometrics; PlyoJam, which combines high-energy HIIT with dance; or Core, which is all about toning up those midsection muscles.

Seconds away from the bustle of Broadway is this tranquil studio where dynamic yoga is the order of the day. Expert teachers put on classes throughout the day encouraging fluid, rhythmic movement that's a real workout. Sign up online or pop by for a drop in class - they run until 9pm on weeknights.

The idea behind DO.OM Yoga is a coming together of music and movement to create an immersive, moving meditation that can take you to places inside yourself that you didn’t know existed. To a soundtrack of doom, drone, ambient, avant-garde and psychedelic you’ll follow a dynamic-restorative vinyasa flow that teeters between tension-release and strength-building. There’s some chat about active and passive postures, the synthesis between sound and silence, and vibrational introspection, which we feel underqualified to comment on, but you can decide for yourself.

They have a weekly class at Hackney Coffee Company on Tuesdays and a monthly session at Ace hotel on the last Friday of the Month.

Sometimes, ya just gotta look out for no. 1. Treat yo'self. Take a dip in the cool waters of self-care. That's what they're all about at Masaj - a boutique wellness space in Cambridge Heath that's 'redefining the concept of massage', in their words. They're all about combatting the harmful effects of city living with bespoke body work and 100% natural products. You can tailor your treatment to your particular needs, focussing on the area of the body that needs the most TLC. Heavenly stuff.

Ceramics sure has become popular in recent times - it makes us wish we'd invested in it rather than cryptocurrency. Turning Earth are regal princes of the trade and this is their second outpost - the light-filled top floor of an old hardware factory which encompasses some 8,500 square feet.

The centre includes a large open-plan membership studio where part-time professional makers, serious hobbyists and beginners work together in a community environment. The space also includes a classroom for ceramics courses for those new to the craft, where 12-week courses are taught by the pros. Demand is high and so is the price for these courses, but if you like ceramics then why the heck not.

Enter ‘Flowing Pilates’. Yes it may sound calm and relaxing, but this 60-minute class was anything but, based on what we endured. Pre-class pedicures are advised as hand-on-foot action from instructor Charles is inevitable throughout.

With just 6 reformer machines, the class is pretty intimate and the space is minimal but the atmosphere makes up for it with chilled music and a tranquil vibe. The workout itself involved everything from squats to ab crunches and inner thigh workouts using a Pilates ring.

Think of Bethnal Green and you might not immediately be envisioning yourself stripped to the waist, with sweat trickling down your face, contemplating the meaning of life. But that could be the reality at the York Hall Spa experience, one of the most affordable spas in town.

Though they offer a range of treatments here, the Thermal Spa experience is the golden ticket, set in one of London's oldest Turkish baths. For three hours you can run (don't run) wild, dipping into two aroma steam rooms, Turkish baths (Tepidarium, Caldarium and Laconium), a sauna, ice fountain, monsoon shower, bucket shower, plunge pool, Hammam and a relaxation lounge. You'll be getting hot, cold and wet in every way known to man. This comes in at £26, but be warned, the service and organisation here can occasionally reflect that budget price.

If you're one of those types who loses concentration quicker than a sloth and can't hold down a hobby, after a drop-in session at Gravity Circus you'll definitely have one on lockdown. From aerialists, acrobats, Chinese pole artists to contortionists, all sorts of freakish circus talent is born here.

Drop-in classes are available for all levels, so don't be put off if you have zero experience - we all have to start somewhere after all. Drop-in training classes begin from £6.50 whereas their 6-week courses are a little more on the expensive side.

The sight of lubricated grown men in Spandex might initially be a sight for sore eyes, but it's definitely not something to be taken too seriously... This is London's School of Lucha Libre - a freestyle Mexican wrestling class where literally anything could happen. One thing we do know is that there'll be plenty of slam dunks, kick drops and hilarious moments prompted by their ridiculous outfits. Beginner classes take place on Mondays, intermediates on Tuesdays and the pros on Wednesdays - so better not get them mixed up! See you in the ring.

Since 1978, a time when the mind had no idea how full it could really be, London Buddhist Centre has been aligning the practice of Buddhism with the general rough and tumble of city living. At their Bethnal Green temple, in a disused fire station, they’ve built up a thriving Buddhist community with drop in meditation classes, yoga and a veggie cafe.

These classes, taking place in the afternoon and on some evenings, are often free but encourage a donation, so please do give a few bucks, because this is a nourishing, important community space. It is, and always will be, a place that’s open for all - with no expectation of Buddhist involvement.

Totally zen, itty-bitty yoga studio in the wonderful Stamford Works complex. They do rocket, vinyasa, and jivamukti flow classes in an airy, plant-laden space. Sundays are a real treat: go for the yoga + brunch class, catered by the wonderful East Brunswick next door. Drop in is £12, which puts this studio on the cheaper end of the spectrum.

Train with qualified and experienced amateur boxing champion coaches, and learn how to box your way to the top. With a good mix of both lads and lassies, these classes welcome all walks of life. Whether you're a beginner, just want a hardcore fitness workout or are on the brink of becoming Rocky II - you'll find something here to suit all abilities.

Just £15 for 3 trial classes, after which you can decide whether you want to join proper. Classes go until 9pm most weeknights.
